   "source": [
    "# Module 6: Introduction to Linear Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "## 1. From Inference to Relationship Modeling\n",
    "\n",
    "Previous modules focused primarily on statistical inference techniques such as:\n",
    "- Estimation\n",
    "- Hypothesis testing\n",
    "- ANOVA\n",
    "- Categorical association analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "These methods allowed us to answer questions such as:\n",
    "- Are two population means different?\n",
    "- Is a treatment effect statistically significant?\n",
    "- Are variables associated?\n",
    "- Does a factor influence outcomes?\n",
    "\n",
    "However, many real-world systems involve continuous relationships rather than simple group comparisons.\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples include:\n",
    "- How sales change with advertising expenditure\n",
    "- How exam scores change with study time\n",
    "- How house prices change with area\n",
    "- How demand changes with price\n",
    "- How temperature affects energy consumption\n",
    "\n",
    "These problems require a different statistical framework: **Regression Analysis**\n",
    "\n",
    "Regression is one of the most powerful and widely used tools in statistics, data science, economics, finance, engineering, and machine learning."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. The Core Goal of Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "The central objective of regression is **modeling relationships between variables**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Specifically:\n",
    "- One variable acts as the **predictor** (X)\n",
    "- Another variable acts as the **response** (Y)\n",
    "\n",
    "The inferential question becomes:\n",
    "\n",
    "**How does Y change as X changes?**\n",
    "\n",
    "Regression moves statistics beyond simple comparisons toward mathematical modeling of relationships."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Import required libraries\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from scipy import stats\n",
    "import statsmodels.api as sm\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set style for better visualizations\n",
    "plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-darkgrid')\n",
    "sns.set_palette(\"husl\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set random seed for reproducibility\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Libraries imported successfully!\")\n",
    "print(f\"NumPy version: {np.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Pandas version: {pd.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Statsmodels version: {sm.__version__}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. What Is Linear Regression?\n",
    "\n",
    "Linear regression models the relationship between variables using a **straight-line equation**.\n",
    "\n",
    "The simplest form is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$Y = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 X + \\varepsilon$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "- $Y$ = response variable (dependent variable)\n",
    "- $X$ = predictor variable (independent variable)\n",
    "- $\\beta_0$ = intercept (value of Y when X = 0)\n",
    "- $\\beta_1$ = slope coefficient (change in Y per unit change in X)\n",
    "- $\\varepsilon$ = random error term\n",
    "\n",
    "This equation forms the foundation of **simple linear regression**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Demonstrate the linear relationship concept\n",
    "X_demo = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Case 1: Positive relationship (beta1 > 0)\n",
    "beta0_pos, beta1_pos = 2, 1.5\n",
    "Y_pos = beta0_pos + beta1_pos * X_demo\n",
    "\n",
    "# Case 2: Negative relationship (beta1 < 0)\n",
    "beta0_neg, beta1_neg = 10, -0.8\n",
    "Y_neg = beta0_neg + beta1_neg * X_demo\n",
    "\n",
    "# Case 3: No relationship (beta1 = 0)\n",
    "beta0_zero, beta1_zero = 5, 0\n",
    "Y_zero = beta0_zero + beta1_zero * X_demo\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].plot(X_demo, Y_pos, 'b-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(f'Positive Relationship ($\\\\beta_1 = {beta1_pos}$)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('X')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('Y')\n",
    "axes[0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].plot(X_demo, Y_neg, 'r-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(f'Negative Relationship ($\\\\beta_1 = {beta1_neg}$)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('X')\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('Y')\n",
    "axes[1].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[2].plot(X_demo, Y_zero, 'g-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[2].set_title(f'No Relationship ($\\\\beta_1 = {beta1_zero}$)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[2].set_xlabel('X')\n",
    "axes[2].set_ylabel('Y')\n",
    "axes[2].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.suptitle('Linear Relationships: The Meaning of Slope', fontsize=14, y=1.02)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Why the Relationship Is Called \"Linear\"\n",
    "\n",
    "The term **linear** refers to the relationship being linear in the parameters $\\beta_0, \\beta_1$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Graphically, the relationship forms a **straight line**.\n",
    "\n",
    "This implies:\n",
    "- Constant rate of change\n",
    "- Additive structure\n",
    "- Proportional directional effect\n",
    "\n",
    "**Directional implications:**\n",
    "- If $\\beta_1 > 0$: $X \\uparrow \\Rightarrow Y \\uparrow$ (positive relationship)\n",
    "- If $\\beta_1 < 0$: $X \\uparrow \\Rightarrow Y \\downarrow$ (negative relationship)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. The Meaning of the Intercept ($\\beta_0$)\n",
    "\n",
    "The intercept $\\beta_0$ represents the **predicted value of Y when X = 0**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Interpretation depends heavily on context.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Examples:**\n",
    "- Baseline salary (years of experience = 0)\n",
    "- Starting measurement (time = 0)\n",
    "- Default system output (input = 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "In some applications, the intercept has practical meaning. In others, it serves primarily as a mathematical anchor for the regression line."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. The Meaning of the Slope ($\\beta_1$)\n",
    "\n",
    "The slope coefficient $\\beta_1$ measures the **average change in Y** associated with a **one-unit increase in X**.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\beta_1 = \\frac{\\Delta Y}{\\Delta X}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Examples:**\n",
    "- Increase in sales per advertising dollar\n",
    "- Increase in salary per year of experience\n",
    "- Increase in crop yield per fertilizer unit\n",
    "\n",
    "The slope is the **central measure of relationship strength and direction**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Generating Sample Regression Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's generate realistic data to demonstrate regression concepts."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Generate synthetic data: Advertising Spend vs Sales\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "n_samples = 100\n",
    "\n",
    "# True relationship: Sales = 50 + 3*Advertising + error\n",
    "true_intercept = 50\n",
    "true_slope = 3\n",
    "\n",
    "advertising = np.random.uniform(0, 20, n_samples)\n",
    "error = np.random.normal(0, 8, n_samples)  # Random noise\n",
    "sales = true_intercept + true_slope * advertising + error\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create DataFrame\n",
    "df_sales = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'Advertising': advertising,\n",
    "    'Sales': sales\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"First 10 rows of the dataset:\")\n",
    "print(df_sales.head(10))\n",
    "print(f\"\\nDataset shape: {df_sales.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nBasic statistics:\")\n",
    "print(df_sales.describe())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize the relationship\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plt.scatter(df_sales['Advertising'], df_sales['Sales'], alpha=0.6, edgecolors='black', linewidth=0.5)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Advertising Spend ($1000s)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sales ($1000s)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.title('Scatter Plot: Advertising vs Sales', fontsize=14)\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the true regression line\n",
    "x_line = np.array([0, 20])\n",
    "y_line = true_intercept + true_slope * x_line\n",
    "plt.plot(x_line, y_line, 'r--', linewidth=2, label=f'True Line: Sales = {true_intercept} + {true_slope}*Ad')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8. The Error Term ($\\varepsilon$)\n",
    "\n",
    "Real-world data never falls perfectly on a line.\n",
    "\n",
    "The error term $\\varepsilon$ captures **variability unexplained by the regression model**.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Sources of error include:**\n",
    "- Measurement error\n",
    "- Omitted variables\n",
    "- Randomness\n",
    "- Human variability\n",
    "- Environmental fluctuations\n",
    "\n",
    "$$Y = \\text{Systematic Component} + \\text{Random Component}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Regression attempts to model the systematic structure while acknowledging unavoidable randomness."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Demonstrate the concept of error\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Subplot 1: Data without error\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
    "sales_no_error = true_intercept + true_slope * advertising\n",
    "plt.scatter(advertising, sales_no_error, alpha=0.6, color='green')\n",
    "plt.plot(x_line, y_line, 'r-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Advertising', fontsize=11)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sales', fontsize=11)\n",
    "plt.title('Perfect Linear Relationship (No Error)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Subplot 2: Data with error\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
    "plt.scatter(advertising, sales, alpha=0.6, color='blue')\n",
    "plt.plot(x_line, y_line, 'r-', linewidth=2, label='True Relationship')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show some error arrows\n",
    "for i in range(0, n_samples, 15):\n",
    "    pred = true_intercept + true_slope * advertising[i]\n",
    "    plt.vlines(advertising[i], pred, sales[i], colors='gray', linestyles='dotted', alpha=0.7)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Advertising', fontsize=11)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sales', fontsize=11)\n",
    "plt.title('Realistic Data with Error ($\\\\varepsilon$)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Variance of error term: {error.var():.2f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Standard deviation of error: {error.std():.2f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9. Building the Regression Line\n",
    "\n",
    "Given sample data $(x_1, y_1), (x_2, y_2), ..., (x_n, y_n)$, we estimate the regression line:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\hat{Y} = b_0 + b_1 X$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "- $b_0$ estimates $\\beta_0$ (intercept)\n",
    "- $b_1$ estimates $\\beta_1$ (slope)\n",
    "\n",
    "The estimated line is called the **least squares regression line**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Fit linear regression using scikit-learn\n",
    "X_fit = df_sales[['Advertising']].values\n",
    "y_fit = df_sales['Sales'].values\n",
    "\n",
    "model = LinearRegression()\n",
    "model.fit(X_fit, y_fit)\n",
    "\n",
    "b1 = model.coef_[0]  # Estimated slope\n",
    "b0 = model.intercept_  # Estimated intercept\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Estimated regression equation:\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sales = {b0:.2f} + {b1:.2f} * Advertising\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nTrue equation (what generated the data):\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sales = {true_intercept} + {true_slope} * Advertising + error\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nEstimation error:\")\n",
    "print(f\"Intercept error: {abs(b0 - true_intercept):.2f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Slope error: {abs(b1 - true_slope):.4f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize the estimated regression line\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plt.scatter(df_sales['Advertising'], df_sales['Sales'], alpha=0.6, edgecolors='black', linewidth=0.5, label='Actual data')\n",
    "plt.plot(x_line, true_intercept + true_slope * x_line, 'r--', linewidth=2, label=f'True line: Y = {true_intercept} + {true_slope}X')\n",
    "plt.plot(x_line, b0 + b1 * x_line, 'b-', linewidth=2, label=f'Estimated line: Y = {b0:.2f} + {b1:.2f}X')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Advertising Spend ($1000s)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sales ($1000s)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.title('Simple Linear Regression: Estimated vs True Line', fontsize=14)\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 10. The Least Squares Principle\n",
    "\n",
    "The regression line is chosen using the **least squares method**.\n",
    "\n",
    "The objective is minimizing the total squared prediction error:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\sum (y_i - \\hat{y}_i)^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "- $y_i$ = observed value\n",
    "- $\\hat{y}_i$ = predicted value\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why square the errors?**\n",
    "1. Prevents positive and negative errors from canceling\n",
    "2. Penalizes large errors heavily\n",
    "3. Produces mathematically tractable optimization\n",
    "\n",
    "Large prediction errors receive disproportionately larger penalties."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Demonstrate least squares optimization\n",
    "possible_slopes = np.linspace(0, 6, 100)\n",
    "possible_intercepts = np.linspace(30, 70, 100)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate SSE for different slope values (fixing intercept at true value)\n",
    "sse_values = []\n",
    "for slope in possible_slopes:\n",
    "    predictions = true_intercept + slope * advertising\n",
    "    sse = np.sum((sales - predictions)**2)\n",
    "    sse_values.append(sse)\n",
    "\n",
    "optimal_idx = np.argmin(sse_values)\n",
    "optimal_slope = possible_slopes[optimal_idx]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
    "plt.plot(possible_slopes, sse_values, 'b-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "plt.axvline(x=true_slope, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'True slope = {true_slope}')\n",
    "plt.axvline(x=optimal_slope, color='g', linestyle='--', label=f'Optimal slope = {optimal_slope:.2f}')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Slope ($\\\\beta_1$)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Errors (SSE)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.title('Least Squares: Minimizing SSE', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
    "n_points = 20\n",
    "sample_indices = np.random.choice(range(n_samples), n_points, replace=False)\n",
    "plt.scatter(advertising[sample_indices], sales[sample_indices], alpha=0.7, edgecolors='black')\n",
    "pred_line = b0 + b1 * advertising[sample_indices]\n",
    "plt.plot([advertising[sample_indices], advertising[sample_indices]], \n",
    "         [sales[sample_indices], pred_line], 'r-', alpha=0.5, linewidth=1)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Advertising', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sales', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.title('Residuals (Prediction Errors) Visualization', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Minimum SSE: {min(sse_values):.2f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Optimal slope from grid search: {optimal_slope:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"OLS estimated slope: {b1:.4f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 11. Residuals\n",
    "\n",
    "Residuals measure prediction error:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$e_i = y_i - \\hat{y}_i$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpretation:**\n",
    "- Positive residual ($e_i > 0$) → Underprediction (actual > predicted)\n",
    "- Negative residual ($e_i < 0$) → Overprediction (actual < predicted)\n",
    "- Small residual ($e_i \\approx 0$) → Accurate prediction\n",
    "\n",
    "Residual analysis is critically important for diagnosing model quality."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Calculate predictions and residuals\n",
    "predictions = model.predict(X_fit)\n",
    "residuals = y_fit - predictions\n",
    "\n",
    "df_results = df_sales.copy()\n",
    "df_results['Predicted_Sales'] = predictions\n",
    "df_results['Residual'] = residuals\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"First 15 observations with predictions and residuals:\")\n",
    "print(df_results.head(15).to_string())\n",
    "print(f\"\\nResidual statistics:\")\n",
    "print(f\"Mean of residuals: {residuals.mean():.6f} (should be close to 0)\")\n",
    "print(f\"Standard deviation of residuals: {residuals.std():.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sum of residuals: {residuals.sum():.6f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize residuals\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 1: Residuals vs Fitted values\n",
    "axes[0, 0].scatter(predictions, residuals, alpha=0.6, edgecolors='black')\n",
    "axes[0, 0].axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_xlabel('Fitted Values', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Residuals', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_title('Residuals vs Fitted Values', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[0, 0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 2: Histogram of residuals\n",
    "axes[0, 1].hist(residuals, bins=20, edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7)\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_xlabel('Residuals', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_title('Histogram of Residuals', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[0, 1].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 3: Q-Q plot for normality check\n",
    "stats.probplot(residuals, dist=\"norm\", plot=axes[1, 0])\n",
    "axes[1, 0].set_title('Q-Q Plot: Normality Check', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[1, 0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 4: Residuals vs Order\n",
    "axes[1, 1].plot(range(len(residuals)), residuals, 'o', alpha=0.6)\n",
    "axes[1, 1].axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Observation Order', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_ylabel('Residuals', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_title('Residuals vs Observation Order', fontsize=12)\n",
    "axes[1, 1].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 12. Model Significance and Hypothesis Testing\n",
    "\n",
    "Once the regression line is estimated, we evaluate whether the relationship itself is statistically meaningful.\n",
    "\n",
    "The central hypothesis is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$H_0: \\beta_1 = 0 \\quad \\text{(No Linear Relationship)}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$H_A: \\beta_1 \\neq 0 \\quad \\text{(Linear Relationship Exists)}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "A statistically significant slope suggests evidence of a linear relationship between X and Y."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Perform hypothesis testing using statsmodels\n",
    "X_with_const = sm.add_constant(X_fit)\n",
    "model_sm = sm.OLS(y_fit, X_with_const).fit()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"=\" * 70)\n",
    "print(\"REGRESSION RESULTS WITH HYPOTHESIS TESTS\")\n",
    "print(\"=\" * 70)\n",
    "print(model_sm.summary())\n",
    "print(\"=\" * 70)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Extract key hypothesis test results\n",
    "print(\"\\nKEY HYPOTHESIS TEST RESULTS:\")\n",
    "print(\"-\" * 40)\n",
